<question xmlns='http://www.gradians.com'>
  <statement>
    <tex>%text
Let $\ora{a}=\vector{1}{4}{2}$, $\ora{b}=\vector{3}{-2}{7}$ and
$\ora{c}=\vector{2}{-1}{4}$. Find a vector $\ora{p}$ which is 
perpendicular to both $\ora{a}$ and $\ora{b}$ and whose
dot product with c, $\ora{p}\cdot\ora{c}=18$.
%</tex>
  </statement>
  <step>
    <context>%text
If a vector $\ora{p}$ is perpendicular to both$\ora{a}$
and $\ora{b}$, and $\lambda$ is some scalar, can we say
the following about $\ora{p}$?
%</context>
    <tex correct='true'>\ora{p}=\lambda(\ora{a}\times \ora{b})</tex>
    <tex>\ora{p}=\lambda (\ora{a}+ \ora{b})</tex>
    <reason>%text
Any vector perpendicular to $\ora{a}$ and $\ora{b}$ is
parallel to $(\ora{a}\times \ora{b})$. Therefore, $\ora{p}$ must 
be a scalar multiple of $(\ora{a}\times \ora{b})$.
%
</reason>
  </step>
  <step>
    <context>%text
Given that $\ora{p}\cdot \ora{c}=18$ and $\ora{p}=\lambda(\ora{a}\times \ora{b})$,
what is $\lambda$?
%</context>
    <tex correct='true'>\lambda=2</tex>
    <tex>\lambda=9</tex>
    <reason>\begin{align}
  &amp;\ora{p}\cdot \ora{c}=18 \\
  \implies &amp;\lambda(\ora{a}\times \ora{b})\cdot \ora{c}=18 \\
  \implies &amp;\lambda\left\vert\begin{array}{ccc}
    1 &amp; 4 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; -2 &amp; 7 \\ 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 4\end{array}\right\vert=18 \\
  \implies &amp;\lambda \left[1(-8+7)-4(12-14)+2(-3+4)\right]=18 \\
  \implies &amp;\lambda \left[-1+8+2\right]=18 \\
  \implies &amp;\lambda=2
\end{align}</reason>
  </step>
  <step>
    <context>%text
$\ora{a}=\vector{1}{4}{2}$, $\ora{b}=\vector{3}{-2}{7}$ and 
$\lambda=2$. $\ora{p}=\lambda(\ora{a}\times \ora{b})$. Find $\ora{p}$?
%
</context>
    <tex correct='true'>\ora{p}=\vector{64}{-2}{-28}</tex>
    <tex>\ora{p}=\vector{64}{2}{-28}</tex>
    <reason>\begin{align}
  \ora{a}\times\ora{b}&amp;=\left\vert\begin{array}{ccc}
      \hat i &amp; \hat j &amp; \hat k \\ 1 &amp; 4 &amp; 2 \\ 3 &amp; -2 &amp; 7
    \end{array}\right\vert \\
    &amp;=\vector{(28+4)}{-(7-6)}{(-2-12)} \\
    &amp;=\vector{32}{-1}{-14}
\end{align} \\
\therefore \ora{p}=2(\vector{32}{-1}{-14})=\vector{64}{-2}{-28}</reason>
  </step>
  <choices>
    <tex>\ora{p}=\vector{64}{2}{28}</tex>
    <tex>\ora{p}=\vector{64}{2}{-28}</tex>
    <tex correct='true'>\ora{p}=\vector{64}{-2}{-28}</tex>
    <tex>\ora{p}=\vector{32}{-1}{-14}</tex>
  </choices>
</question>